Now the compile-time lookup action — this is where the magic happens:
compileOperator op left right; {
    /*****************************************************
        Look up the operator in inlineOps. If both
        operand types are known and match an inline entry,
        emit the direct LLVM instruction. Otherwise fall
        back to a native method call.
    *****************************************************/
    leftType  = left.resolvedType;
    rightType = right.resolvedType;

    entry = inlineOps[op.tag];
    while entry;
        if entry.leftType == leftType AND
           entry.rightType == rightType;
            emitInline(entry.llvmOp, left, right);
            return;
        entry = entry.next;

    /*****************************************************
        No inline match found - emit native call instead
    *****************************************************/
    if native = nativeRegistry[op.tag];
        emitNativeCall(native, left, right);
    else
        print "compileOperator: no handler for" op.tag:;
}
And the emitInline and emitNativeCall actions are where we cross the boundary into C++:
emitInline llvmOp left right; {
